This course is an investigation of some of the central questions about the nature of morality: Are moral judgments objective and justifiable? Can moral disagreements be resolved rationally? How are we to understand the idea of a good life, and what is the relationship between a good life and morality? To what extent can we be held responsible for our conduct? Readings are from both contemporary and historical sources, and concern both practical problems (e.g. abortion, euthanasia, or resource conservation) and theoretical issues.&#8232;

Students described the course as “awesome,” “fascinating” and “stimulating.” Overall, it was a “good” class that explores what different ethicists said, where their ideas came from, and how they compare to other theories. Many expressed surprise at how “interesting” they found the material. They especially liked learning modern approaches to ethics in addition to the classical. The lecture format of the course wasn’t ideal; students would have preferred a smaller class for more interactive discussion. Even though they found it “a little” to “very repetitive” and even “slow-paced,” students felt that they “learned a lot.”&#8232;&#8232;

Students described Professor Martin as “amazing,” “eager,” and “incredibly engaging.” She was overwhelmingly described as “nice,” and very “helpful and available” when it comes to answering questions and exploring students’ thoughts. She had an “amazing ability to stimulate interest” in ethics. Although a bit repetitive, she was a “great lecturer” and “made the class very interactive and interesting,” because she was very “animated” during lecture. She teaches the course material well, skilled at making it accessible to students. The only complaints were a request for more office hours and a feeling that lectures were repetitive and sometimes scattered. Overall, students commended Professor Martin’s instruction. One student described her as one of the “best professors at Penn.” &#8232;&#8232;

A combination of philosophy majors and non-philosophy majors took the course, but all felt “captivated” by the topic of ethics. Philosophy majors with more background might be bored by repetitive lectures, whereas non-majors might appreciate the redundant emphasis on unfamiliar topics. Readings are “very complex and dense,” making the course “difficult.” Frequent quizzes on readings force you keep up, but some students felt that readings weren’t necessary until the final. However, even those who found it “tough” felt that the course is “interesting for someone curious about philosophy or ethics.”

This course is an investigation of some of the central questions about the nature of morality: Are moral judgments objective and justifiable? Can moral disagreements be resolved rationally? How are we to understand the idea of a good life, and what is the relationship between a good life and morality? To what extent can we be held responsible for our conduct? Readings are drawn from both contemporary and historical sources, and concern both practical problems (e.g. abortion, euthanasia, or resource conservation) and theoretical issues.
Students were satisfied with the fascinating material and what was “overall a pretty interesting course.” One student reflected, “It changed a lot of the ways which I think about the world.”&#8232;
Professor Meyer got both positive and negative feedback from students. He is clearly very knowledgeable and “seemed to know a lot about the subject.” However, some students found his lectures “difficult to understand,” partially because he is “not very good at explaining the subject matter,” and partly because he assumed students had more background knowledge than they all did. Students disliked that class felt “totally unstructured” and involved only Professor Meyer lecturing, with little room for discussion. Further, he demonstrated a “tendency to push his own point of view rather than being an unbiased teacher.” He seemed to find “his own views the ‘correct’ views” and also occasionally favored some students over others. However, he is a “very nice” instructor, who is always “open to problems and questions,” completely willing to help students, even engaging in “deep conversations” via e-mail. &#8232;
&#8232;The workload didn’t seem to bother students, although several felt that the instructor “played favorites,” and his preferences were reflected in grades. They also thought that he “never made it clear as to what he was expecting,” so they felt “left in the dark on assignments.” This course is strongly recommended to those who have an interest in “philosophy, politics, or moral thinking in general.” For a student completely new to philosophy, this “probably isn’t a bad place to start.” However, the class is “very challenging” and would be a “real struggle” for someone without any interest in the topic. “Content may be too deep for the only slightly interested student.”
